thread.title: '1 Extra Month': NASA's Sunita Williams' Return from ISS Delayed Again
thread.title_full: '1 Extra Month': NASA's Sunita Williams' Return from ISS Delayed Again

author: ET Online
title: '1 Extra Month': NASA's Sunita Williams' Return from ISS Delayed Again
text:
Jan 10, 2025
NASA announced that astronauts Sunita Williams and Butch Wilmore will remain aboard the International Space Station (ISS) until at least late March 2025 due to a delay in launching their replacements.
Image Source: Agencies
The SpaceX Crew-9 mission, including Williams, Wilmore, Nick Hague, and Aleksandr Gorbunov, will return after the Crew-10 team reaches the ISS, ensuring a smooth crew transition.
Image Source: Agencies
In August, NASA had indicated a February 2025 return for the two astronauts. However, this timeline has been pushed back due to delays in launching the next crew.
Image Source: Agencies
The postponement stems from SpaceX needing additional time to prepare a new capsule for the next crew, shifting their launch to no earlier than late March 2025.
Image Source: Agencies
NASA prefers overlapping crews at the ISS to ensure seamless operations. The delay maintains this policy, despite extending Crew-9â€™s mission.
Image Source: Agencies
Wilmore and Williams initially arrived at the ISS in June 2024 aboard Boeing's Starliner spacecraft, intending to stay for a short eight-day mission that later extended into a longer deployment.
Image Source: Agencies
NASA considered using a different SpaceX capsule for the Crew-10 launch but opted to wait for the new capsule to avoid operational risks.
Image Source: Agencies
NASA confirmed the ISS is well-stocked with essentials, including food, water, clothing, and oxygen, thanks to two resupply missions completed in November 2024.
Image Source: Agencies
The resupply missions also included special items for the crew to celebrate the holidays, ensuring their well-being during the extended mission.
Image Source: Agencies
